------------------------------------------------------------
RECOMMENDED REAL-WORLD WORKFLOW
------------------------------------------------------------

Step 1: test raw palette first
------------------------------

    python3 palette_gen.py /path/to/wallpaper.png --surface-style neutral --debug

If palette looks sane:
- dark ramp is stable
- accent is usable
- text ramp is readable

Step 2: build / refresh the theme
---------------------------------

    python3 theme_build.py /path/to/wallpaper.png --surface-style neutral

Step 3: inspect generated files
-------------------------------

    sed -n '1,40p' ~/.local/share/themes/Dorakura-Kyoto/color.ini
    sed -n '1,80p' ~/.local/share/themes/Dorakura-Kyoto/gtk-2.0/colors.rc
    sed -n '1,120p' ~/.local/share/themes/Dorakura-Kyoto/gtk-3.0/widgets/00-palette.css

Step 4: manually tune widget modules
------------------------------------

Priority files:
- 20-buttons.css
- 30-entries.css
- 70-controls.css
- 90-app-nemo.css

These will give the biggest visible improvement first.

------------------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT ARCHITECTURE NOTE
------------------------------------------------------------

theme_build.py imports palette_gen.py directly.

This means:
- same interpreter
- same process
- no subprocess
- no extra Python instance
- direct function calls
- direct dict/string returns

This is the correct design.

Bad approach:
    subprocess.run(["python3", "palette_gen.py", ...])

Good approach:
    from palette_gen import generate_base16_palette

------------------------------------------------------------
SAFE DEFAULTS
------------------------------------------------------------

Recommended default for almost everything:

    --surface-style neutral

Why:
- better dark surface discipline
- safer GTK defaults
- less over-colored UI
- still preserves good accent extraction

Use tinted only when you explicitly want:
- stronger mood
- more stylized panels
- wallpaper-reactive drama

